1110d38b-33c2-4cab-b4e0-3596aac4acee.00a739f4-5da1-4b16-be6c-b57e69520c56.prompt=String to Append \: 1110d38b-33c2-4cab-b4e0-3596aac4acee.043acd2d-9410-47c9-8315-0f53d2d402e3.prompt=Enter a value for kerberosConfFile 1110d38b-33c2-4cab-b4e0-3596aac4acee.0729617b-0ff7-402b-8f6a-d0a351b7ee8f.prompt=Enter a value for authType 1110d38b-33c2-4cab-b4e0-3596aac4acee.176e2bb9-0b51-456d-8c85-497ae1dec307.prompt=Enter a value for socketTimeout 1110d38b-33c2-4cab-b4e0-3596aac4acee.18afa46a-7345-453a-a8bf-6df3eda08b32.description=
If the input dateFormat is not specified, it converts a date in the format of date/time of OO Central Server's, which is dependant on the Java locale, to a date either in the format of date/time of OO Central Server's or in the format specified in the input outFormat. 

If the input dateFormat is specified, it converts a date in the format in dateFormat to a date either in the format of date/time of OO Central Server's or in the format specified in the input outFormat.

You can use flow "Get Current Date and Time" to check upon the default date/time format.  

For exmaple, if OO Central Server's locale is English, the input dateFormat is empty and the input outFormat is empty, the input date should be in the format of "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the user specifies dateFormat as "dd-MM-YYYY HH\:mm\:ss", the input date should be in the format of "13-07-2006 10\:04\:08". If the input outFormat is empty, the result will be "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the input outFormat is "yyyy-MM-dd", the result will be "2006-07-13". The dateFormat for "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:078 AM" is "MMM dd, yyyy HH\:mm\:ss a". 


Specify the date format with the following patterns\:

Letter 	Date or Time Component 	Presentation 	Examples
G 	Era designator 	Text 	                     AD
y 	Year 	                     Year 	                     1996; 96
M 	Month in year 	Month 	                     July; Jul; 07
w 	Week in year 	Number 	                     27
W 	Week in month 	Number 	                     2
D 	Day in year 	                     Number 	                     189
d 	Day in month 	Number 	                     10
F 	Day of week in month 	Number 	                     2
E 	Day in week   	Text 	                     Tuesday; Tue
a 	Am/pm marker 	Text 	                     PM
H 	Hour in day (0-23) 	Number 	                     0
k 	Hour in day (1-24) 	Number 	                     24
K 	Hour in am/pm (0-11) 	Number 	                     0
h 	Hour in am/pm (1-12) 	Number 	                     12
m 	Minute in hour 	Number 	                     30
s 	Second in minute 	Number 	                     55
S 	Millisecond 	                     Number 	                     978
z 	Time zone 	                     General time zone 	Pacific Standard Time; PST; GMT-08\:00
Z 	Time zone 	                     RFC 822 time zone 	-0800

So, for example\: the date "2006-07-10 15\:16\:14.766 PDT" would have the dateFormat "yyyy-MM-dd HH\:mm\:ss.SSS z".

You can also use single quotes (') to avoid text interpretation. The quoted text will simply be copied into the output string during formatting (if present in the outFormat) or matched against the input string during parsing (if present in the dateFormat). For example, the date value "2006-07-10T15\:16\:14.766Z" would have the dateFormat "yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSS'Z'". 


Inputs\:
date - The date to parse. If the input dateFormat is empty, the date must be in the format of date/time of OO Central Server's, which is dependant on the Java locale. If the input dateFormat is not empty, the date must be in the format specified in the input dateFormat.
dateFormat - The format of the input date. 
dateLocaleLang - The locale language for input dateFormat string. For example,  en or ja.  It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty. 
dateLocaleCountry - The locale country for input dateFormat string. For example, US or JP.  It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty or dateLocaleLang is empty. 
outFormat - The format of the output date/time. If it is empty, the output date/time will be in the format of date/time of OO Cental Server's, which is dependant on the Java locale.
outLocaleLang - The locale language for output string. For example,  en or ja. It will be ignored if outFormat is empty. 
outLocaleCountry - The locale country for output string. For example, US or JP. It will be ignored if outFormat is empty or outLocaleLang is empty.

Responses\:
success - The date was converted.
failure - The date could not be converted.

Result\:
The date in the new format.
The date in the new format.
1110d38b-33c2-4cab-b4e0-3596aac4acee.1ad0d7a9-08ac-4059-bffa-c500021547a3.prompt=Enter a value for trustPassword 1110d38b-33c2-4cab-b4e0-3596aac4acee.1ec452f8-a411-400a-9e02-dba9bc4ea98f.description=
Accepts an object in the JavaScript Object Notation format (JSON) and
returns a value for the specified key.

The JSON format encodes objects as a set of unordered key/value pairs, which is
similar to a structure or map in other programming languages.  For example,
   { "city" \: "Palo Alto", 
     "state" \: "CA" }
is an object with two elements one with the name "city" having the value "Palo
Alto", and the other being the name "state" with the value "CA". This operation would 
return "Palo Alto" if user enters "city" as a key.

If the input object contains JSON array, array index can be used in the key input. For example, 
{ "location"\: [
      {"city"\: "Roseville", "country"\: "United States"},
      {"city"\: "Cluj", "country"\: "Romania"},
      {"city"\: "Yehud", "country"\: "Israel"}]    
}
The operation would return "Roseville" if user enters "location[0].city" as a key.

JavaScript objects are useful for representing structured data, and are
especially when used within an array.  For example, an operation that retrieves
a set of incidents from an external system may return the entire list in one
array of incident objects.  The description of the enclosing folder,
/Library/Utility Operations/Container/JavaScript Objects has more examples, and
the JSON format is described completely at http\://www.json.org.

Inputs

   object
      The JavaScript object.  
      The operation will return a failure if it is not a JavaScript object.

   key
      The key in the object to get the value of.

Responses

   success
      The value was successfully returned for the specified key. 

   failure
      There was some error in processing the object, most likely because the
      object is not in valid JavaScript Object Notation or the specified key does not exist in the object.  
      You may wish to use a tool such as http\://www.jsonlint.com/ to help diagnose problems with
      JavaScript Object Notation.

Outputs

   The primary output will be the value for the specified key in the object.

Note

    If the value in JSON object is in scientific notation, the returned output will be converted to an equivalent decimal number. Ex, 2.9e+1 will be converted to 29.

Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults". As a result, the context key whose name is in the keyName input will be appended with the string from the input resultText.

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Returns\:
The the value of the context variable it appended to.

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);

1110d38b-33c2-4cab-b4e0-3596aac4acee.4d79b2cf-7f15-4a53-a5bf-96d9639dc019.prompt=Enter a value for trustKeystore 1110d38b-33c2-4cab-b4e0-3596aac4acee.4e19bccd-160f-4c8e-9718-0680d29569c2.prompt=Artifact ID 1110d38b-33c2-4cab-b4e0-3596aac4acee.50f029df-5ab5-4ec6-9372-03c0a4150bc9.description=
Iterates through a list of values. Modifying the value of the list and delimiter inputs during iteration is not generally supported.

Inputs\:
list - The list to iterate through.
separator - A delimiter that separates elements in the list.

Returns\:
The current element of the list, if the response is has more

Responses\:
has more - Another value was in the list, and has been returned.
has no more - The iterator has gone fully through the list. This response will only be returned once per iteration through the list, a subsequent call to the Iterator will restart the Iteration through the list.
failure - failed to process the list.

Note\: Where the iterator is in the list is tracked by each step's unique id. Therefore you can iterate on the same list from multiple steps simultaneously.

WARNING\: Any step that will use the results of this Iterator operation will, by default, attempt to assign that step's inputs from a flow variable. If this is left checked, then the first element of the iterator will be used for every cycle of iteration.
1110d38b-33c2-4cab-b4e0-3596aac4acee.51df15a7-c615-4a78-8f67-8a307e2bd4c9.description=
This workflow returns the details of the given artifact id.

Inputs-
artifactId –   Artifact  Id
userIdentifier  - User Identifier id
authType - The authentication type that this operation uses when trying to execute the request on the target server.
Valid values\: basic, form, digest, ntlm, kerberos, anonymous (no authentication).
Default value\: anonymous - authentication not used when executing the request.
kerberosConfFile - The path to the Kerberos configuration file. If this input is empty the kdc (Key Distribution Center) and realm will get their values from the full domain name which is obtained from the url of the web server.
timeout - The number of milliseconds to wait for a connection to be established. This input should be assigned a value greater than or equal to zero. A timeout value of zero is an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0.
socketTimeout - The number of milliseconds to wait for the data to be retrieved. This input should be assigned a value greater than or equal to zero. A socketTimeout value of zero is an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0.
useCookies - If true, enables cookie tracking. Cookies will be stored between consecutive calls. This is a boolean input. If a non-boolean value is specified, it will take the default value.
Default value\: true.
followRedirects - If true, the GET command automatically follows redirects. This is a boolean input. If a non-boolean value is specified, it will take the default value.
Default value\: true
proxy - A proxy to use when accessing the web site.
proxyPort - The port on the proxy to connect to.
proxyUsername - The username to use when connecting to the proxy.
proxyPassword - The password to use when connecting to the proxy.
encodeURL - If true, automatically encodes the URL. This is a boolean input. If a non-boolean value is specified, it will take the default value.
Default value\: false.
userAgent - The value that should be used if the HTTP header USER_AGENT has to be overridden.
trustAllRoots - If true, enables weak security over SSL. A SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted CA issued it.
Default value\: true
keystore - URL of the keystore file or local path to it (e.g. %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts). It may be empty if HTTPS client authentication is not to be used.
keystorePassword - Password to unlock the keystore.
trustKeystore - URL of the truststore file or local path to it (e.g. %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts). It may be empty if HTTPS server authentication is not to be used.
trustPassword - Password to unlock the truststore.

Outputs-
name –  name of the artifactr 
displayName – display name of the artifact
artifactType – Artifact type
state – state of the artifact
lifeCycleState –  life cycle state of the artifact
lifeCycleSubState – life cycle sub state of the artifact
document  – returned XML document from API

Evaluates the given 'xpathExpression' and returns the results in a form of an Iterator. The 'type' field tells the users the type of XML result returned. Possible values for 'type' are\: [ELEMENT, ATTRIBUTE, TEXT, OTHER]. This powerful operation can be used to retrieve XML Elements, Attributes, Text or filter based on element names, paths, attributes etc. The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) organization provides the XPath specification (http\://www.w3.org). 

NOTE\: XML using default namespace is not supported by this operation.

Inputs\:
xml - The XML (in the form of a String).
xpathExpression - The XPath expression to evaluate.

Responses\:
has more - Another result was in the list, and has been returned.
failure - Something went wrong.
no more - No more results. This will only be returned once, then iteration restarts.

Returns\:
returnResult - Result evaluated from the XPath expression provided.
type - The type of result.
attributeName - If an attribute is returned, the name of the attribute.

1110d38b-33c2-4cab-b4e0-3596aac4acee.dff44fb7-0135-4602-8ce6-bb943e9b8563.description=
Check to see if the value stored in a specified flow variable, denoted by key, is null.

Inputs\:
keyName - The key to check, i.e. the name of the flow variable.

Returns\: 
The value in the specified key, i.e. flow variable.

Responses\:

notNull - If some value is stored in the key, i.e the flow variable has a value assigned.
1110d38b-33c2-4cab-b4e0-3596aac4acee.e2a7b589-a6d4-4b42-af7f-072858524333.prompt=Enter a value for useCookies 1110d38b-33c2-4cab-b4e0-3596aac4acee.ec310f7d-4e6e-4715-a566-ab825d11ac91.description=
Inserts a new name/value property into a JSON object, where the value is a string. This operation forces the value of the name/vale pair to be a string, no matter what data type it actually is. This means that the  input does not need to be wrapped in quotes as any quotes entered in this input will be escaped, ending up in the properties' value. 
The 'Add JSON Property to Object' operation should be used to add values of type other than string, for example\: another object, an array or a number. 

Examples\: 
1)
    Inputs\:
        jsonObject\: {}
        newPropertyName\: test
        newPropertyValue\: test_value
     Result\:
         { "test"\:"test_value"}
2)
    Inputs\:
        jsonObject\: {}
        newPropertyName\: test
        newPropertyValue\: "test_value"
     Result\:
         { "test"\:"\"test_value\""}
3)
    Inputs\:
        jsonObject\: {}
        newPropertyName\: test
        newPropertyValue\: 1
     Result\:
         { "test"\:"1"}
4)
    Inputs\:
        jsonObject\: {}
        newPropertyName\: test
        newPropertyValue\: [1,2,3,4]
     Result\:
         { "test"\:"[1,2,3,4]"}
     Note the value in the name/value pair above is not a JSON Array, but a plain string that looks like one. 

Inputs\:
    jsonObject - String representation of a JSON object. Objects in JSON are a collection of name value pairs, separated by a colon and surrounded with curly brackets {}. The name must be a string value, and the value can be a single string or any valid JSON object or array.
Examples\: {"one"\:1, "two"\:2}, {"one"\:{"a"\:"a","B"\:"B"}, "two"\:"two", "three"\:[1,2,3.4]}
    newPropertyName - The name of the new property to add to the JSON object. 
Examples\: property1, some_property, another property
    newPropertyValue - The value for the new property. This is interpreted as a string, no matter what the contents of the input. 
Examples\: value1, another value

Results\:
    Result - The JSON array with the inserted element.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully. See the message in  for details.

1110d38b-33c2-4cab-b4e0-3596aac4acee.f3a40bcc-58dc-4c5a-9fe0-23787bd14ad9.description=This will sort a table based upon one column in the table. If all of the entries in that column are numeric the sort will be numeric, otherwise it will be alphabetic. 
Inputs\:
Table\: the table to sort
columnDelimiter - the character used to delimit columns
rowDelimiter - the character used to delimit rows
column - the number of the column to sort on(starting at 1).
reverse - set to "true" to make the sort a reverse sort

Results\:
The sorted table output with the same row and column delimiters

Responses\:
success - if the sort completed
failure - if there was an error, for example the specified column was missing in one or more entries
